ems intriguing that it might be able to discover public static nested classes as tests. I want to clarify how this scanning process works and if it indeed supports these nested test classes. There’s a lot to unpack here regarding the capabilities of JUnit.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering method imports**\\n\\nI’m thinking about method names like `createTestCase`. There's a potential conflict with the annotation `junit.framework.Test`. If the code style is to always import classes, I could use `import junit.framework.Test;` and avoid importing `org.junit.jupiter.api.Test` while annotating with `@org.junit.jupiter.api.Test`. Hmm, I wonder if checkstyle would prohibit fully qualified class names? I should probably search style guidelines to confirm.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ZS68ORzCCDARW7z2Oq6o3aqv|fc_037c3dc5b8fa3c72016a24fdddd4048193aa6d2fdfaa1dee7b", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"junit\\.framework\\.Test|@org\\.junit\\.jupiter\\.api\\.Test|junit\\.framework\\.Test test\" tests/src -g '*.java' | head -50", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 555, "output": 885, "cacheRead": 28160, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29600, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780809158574, "responseId": "resp_037c3dc5b8fa3c72016a24fdc75bf08193a0509dd81ffcad36"}}
